Question:
Partition a list of integers into even and odd numbers.
Input:
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6);

Solutions:

Java 8 Streams partition into even/odd using Collectors.partitioningBy(n -> n % 2 == 0). For input [1,2,3,4,5,6], true(even)=[2,4,6], false(odd)=[1,3,5].

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream list via stream(). Collect with partitioningBy(predicate) creating Map<Boolean, List<Integer>>.

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class PartitionEvenOdd {
    public static Map<Boolean, List<Integer>> partitionEvenOdd(List<Integer> nums) {
        return nums.stream()
                   .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(n -> n % 2 == 0));
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6);
        Map<Boolean, List<Integer>> partitioned = partitionEvenOdd(nums);
        System.out.println("Even: " + partitioned.get(true));
        System.out.println("Odd: " + partitioned.get(false));
    }
}

Prints:
text
Even: [2, 4, 6]
Odd: [1, 3, 5]
Always true/false keys.
â€‹
#Thought Process
partitioningBy binary split via predicate (even true). Single-pass O(n). Default toList() downstream. Access via get(true/false).

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty: {true=[], false=[]}.
Null list: NPE.
Null elements: Predicate NPE.
Zero: Even (true).
